{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d79dcb4e-030d-49c5-9e4a-e67c7e4a61cb","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\nSince your SDK changed, you need the updated workload packages, so:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf builds still fail afterward, try a full clean (`dotnet clean` + delete `bin`/`obj` folders) and rebuild.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77985ea3-60ce-43f3-b80e-5489c8fcb5c0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":241},"id":"dac73d83-119d-4fcb-b44c-0f8da1a3cf3f","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:46:04.230Z","parentId":"c5cfd784-f1fb-4f49-a818-5f0b053791c4"}
